subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Color pattern of preserved specimens
. Body pale yellow (
Fig. 4A
). Outer paleae with amber blade and handle; median plume translucent (
Fig. 4D
). Middle paleae, of the mid-dorsal section of the opercular crown, cherry with dark-amber handle (
Fig. 4E
); mid-ventral paleae, cherry to dark amber from the nape toward the tip (
Fig. 4F
). Inner paleae amber (
Fig. 4G
). Opercular papillae pale yellow. Median ridge with brown eyespots (
Fig. 4C
). Tentacles light brown. Building organ and branchiae pale yellow. Parathoracic chaetae translucent (
Fig. 4
H–I). Abdominal neuropodia with a series of brown points; the last neuropodia completely dark brown (
Fig. 4A
). Abdominal neurochaetae and uncini translucent (
Fig. 4J
). Caudal peduncle dark brown to pale yellow toward distal part (
Fig. 4A
).

Operculum
. Opercular crown and opercular stalk completely fused. Opercular crown conic and circular, protruding in lateral view (
Fig. 4A, B, K
). Three rows of paleae, only two visible: ~50 outer paleae, 22 middle and inner paleae. Outer paleae geniculate with a pair of heterodont teeth, one straight and lacerate, and the other curved; flat blade almost twice longer than wide, serrated margin and without visible transversal thecae; median plume long, slightly longer than the blade, acicular, pectinate and branched distally (
Figs. 2I
, 
4D
). Median plume straight or slightly curved in lateral view. Middle paleae strongly geniculate with straight peak, smooth surface with transversal thecae; sub-circular nape, straight, smooth surface, wider than peak, and large, 1/3 as long as peak in dorsal middle paleae (
Fig. 4E
) and 2/ 
5 in
ventral paleae (
Fig. 4F
); small chin, longer than wide, with margin slightly serrated; sharp tip strongly curved in dorsal paleae (
Fig. 4E
), blunted tip falcate in the ventral (
Fig. 4F
). Inner paleae strongly geniculate with straight serrated peak, eight times longer than wide; nape smooth; tip with filaments (
Fig. 4G
). Papillae small and oval. Oral tentacles unbranched. Median ridge long, almost 1/3 as long as opercular stalk, with marginal eyespots (
Fig. 4C
). Median organ absent. Building organ with ‘U’ shape.

Parathorax
. Three parathoracic segments. Chaetigers with a pair of branchiae. Notopodia with lanceolate chaetae interspersed with capillary chaetae (
Fig. 4H
). Neuropodia with lanceolate chaetae interspersed with small lanceolate chaetae (
Fig. 4I
); neurochaetae thinner than notochaetae.

Distribution. Western Atlantic, from Gulf of Mexico to Southern Brazil (
Nunes et al. 2017
) ( Fig. 13 ).
